# 1.  Executive Summary

This document describes all configuration and code changes made to migrate the af-license-agreement-171817 Django application database backend from Azure Database for PostgreSQL Flexible Server to Azure Cosmos DB for PostgreSQL (Citus-based distributed PostgreSQL). No data migration was required; the change is purely at the connection-configuration and infrastructure-definition level.

Because Cosmos DB for PostgreSQL is fully wire-compatible with standard PostgreSQL, the Django ORM, all models, migrations, ArrayField usage, JSONField usage, psycopg2-binary driver, and CI test containers were left untouched.

# 2.  Scope

**In scope:**

Application settings defaults (settings.py)

Developer environment example configuration (.env.example)

Terraform infrastructure variable definitions and values

CI/CD deploy pipeline variable mapping

Code documentation (module docstring in models.py)

**Out of scope:**

Data migration — not required (new cluster, fresh schema via Django migrate)

Django ORM models, migrations, or query code

psycopg2-binary driver (same driver for both services)

CI test containers (local postgres:15 containers remain correct for unit tests)

Azure infrastructure provisioning (handled by the team after this change)

# 3.  Why Azure Cosmos DB for PostgreSQL

Azure Cosmos DB for PostgreSQL (formerly Hyperscale / Citus) was selected as the migration target for the following reasons:

PostgreSQL wire-protocol compatible — zero ORM code changes required.

Managed, fully-integrated Azure service with private endpoints and SSL enforcement.

Horizontal scale-out capability for future growth (distributed tables via Citus extension).

Supports all PostgreSQL extensions used by the application: ArrayField, JSONField, partial indexes.

Unified Azure resource alongside the existing CosmosDB NoSQL account.

# 4.  Key Connection Differences vs. PostgreSQL Flexible Server

| **Attribute** | **Azure PostgreSQL Flexible Server** | **Azure Cosmos DB for PostgreSQL** |
| --- | --- | --- |
| **Host format** | <server>.postgres.database.azure.com | c-<cluster>.<id>.postgres.cosmos.azure.com |
| **Default DB name** | Configurable (was: mvp6) | citus |
| **Admin user** | Configurable (was: pgadmin) | citus |
| **Port** | 5432 | 5432  (unchanged) |
| **SSL** | sslmode=require  (Azure-only) | sslmode=require  (unchanged) |
| **Driver** | psycopg2-binary | psycopg2-binary  (unchanged) |
| **Django ENGINE** | django.db.backends.postgresql | django.db.backends.postgresql  (unchanged) |

# 5.  Files Changed

## 5.1  app/sql_license_optimizer/settings.py

The Django database configuration defaults were updated to match the Cosmos DB for PostgreSQL defaults so the application connects correctly when environment variables are not explicitly supplied.

**Change 1 — Default database user:**

  # Before

  "USER": os.environ.get("DB_USER", "postgres"),

  # After

  "USER": os.environ.get("DB_USER", "citus"),

**Change 2 — Default database name:**

  # Before

  "NAME": os.environ.get("DB_NAME", "mvp6"),

  # After

  "NAME": os.environ.get("DB_NAME", "citus"),

Note: The existing SSL detection logic (endswith('.azure.com')) was not changed. Cosmos DB for PostgreSQL hostnames end in .postgres.cosmos.azure.com, which already satisfies the condition, so SSL options are applied automatically.

## 5.2  app/.env.example

A dedicated database configuration section was added so developers have a complete reference for the Cosmos DB for PostgreSQL connection variables. The existing CosmosDB NoSQL section was clarified to distinguish it from the relational DB.

**Added section:**

# ============================================================

# Database Configuration — CosmosDB for PostgreSQL

# ============================================================

DB_ENGINE=postgresql

DB_HOST=c-<cluster-name>.<uniqueid>.postgres.cosmos.azure.com

DB_NAME=citus

DB_USER=citus

DB_PASSWORD=your-cosmosdb-postgres-password

DB_PORT=5432

DB_SSL_MODE=require

